Mixed Models

This tutorial extends what was previously introduced in the Single Variant Association Tests tutorial from regression models to mixed models that account for genetic relatedness among samples using the GENESIS R/Bioconductor package. We use the output from the Population Structure and Relatedness Inference tutorial as inputs to our mixed models.

Null Model

Recall that the first step in our association testing procedure is to fit the null model i.e.a model fit under the null hypothesis of no individual variant association. The difference from before is that we will fit a mixed model with the desired outcome phenotype, fixed effect covariates, and a random effect with covariance proportional to the kinship matrix.

Prepare the Data

In addition to the phenotype data that we used previously, we will also use the ancestry PCs and pairwise kinship estimates we created in the previous session. Recall that PCs 1-4 and 7 appear to reflect population structure in our sample, so we will use those to adjust for ancestry in our null model (i.e.the same PCs we used in our PC-Relate analysis). We need to add these PCs to our AnnotatedDataFrame with the phenotype data.

# sample annotation
repo_path <- "https://github.com/UW-GAC/SISG_2022/raw/master"
if (!dir.exists("data")) dir.create("data")
sampfile <- "data/sample_phenotype_annotation.RData"
if (!file.exists(sampfile)) download.file(file.path(repo_path, sampfile), sampfile)
annot <- get(load(sampfile))
library(Biobase)

We can create an (n x n) kinship matrix (KM) from the output of pcrelate using the pcrelateToMatrix function. We set scaleKin = 2 to multiply the kinship values by 2, which gives values on the same scale as the standard GRM (this is relevant for the interpretation of the variance component estimates). This matrix is represented in R as a symmetric matrix object from the Matrix package.

kinfile <- "data/pcrelate.RData"
if (!file.exists(kinfile)) download.file(file.path(repo_path, kinfile), kinfile)
pcrel <- get(load(kinfile))

library(GENESIS)
kinship <- pcrelateToMatrix(pcrel, scaleKin=2, verbose=FALSE)
dim(kinship)
## [1] 1126 1126
kinship[1:5,1:5]
## 5 x 5 Matrix of class "dsyMatrix"

## HG00097  0.026415123  0.995376827 -0.012074626 -0.005885957 -0.004003829
## HG00099  0.001584551 -0.012074626  0.933770584  0.047999718 -0.012532815

# save output
save(kinship, file="data/pcrelate_Matrix.RData")

Fit the Null Model

When running a mixed model analysis, we still fit the null model using the fitNullModel function in GENESIS. Now, we include the kinship matrix in the model with the cov.mat argument, which is used to specify the random effect(s) in the model with covariance structure(s) proportional to the supplied matrix(s). The inclusion of these random effects is what makes this a mixed model, rather than a simple regression model. We also add the ancestry PCs to the list of covariates and allow for heterogeneous residual variance by study with the group.var argument, as before.

nullmod <- fitNullModel(annot, 
                        outcome="height", 
                        covars=c("sex", "age", "study", paste0("PC", c(1:4,7))), 
                        cov.mat=kinship, 
                        group.var="study", 
                        verbose=FALSE)
save(nullmod, file="data/null_mixed_model.RData")

Single-Variant Association Tests

Now we can run single-variant score tests to test for association, accounting for genetic ancestry and genetic relatedness among the subjects. We use the same assocTestSingle function as before; the only difference is that we pass in our new null model.

library(SeqVarTools)
gdsfile <- "data/1KG_phase3_subset_chr1.gds"
if (!file.exists(gdsfile)) download.file(file.path(repo_path, gdsfile), gdsfile)
gdsfmt::showfile.gds(closeall=TRUE) # make sure file is not already open
gds <- seqOpen(gdsfile)

# make the seqVarData object
seqData <- SeqVarData(gds, sampleData=annot)

# make the iterator object
iterator <- SeqVarBlockIterator(seqData, verbose=FALSE)

# run the single-variant association test
assoc <- assocTestSingle(iterator, 
                         null.model = nullmod)
## # of selected samples: 1,126

We make the usual QQ plot, filtering to variants with minor allele count (MAC) \(\geq 5\).

library(ggplot2)
qqPlot <- function(pval) {
    pval <- pval[!is.na(pval)]
    n <- length(pval)
    x <- 1:n
    dat <- data.frame(obs=sort(pval),
                      exp=x/n,
                      upper=qbeta(0.025, x, rev(x)),
                      lower=qbeta(0.975, x, rev(x)))
    
    ggplot(dat, aes(-log10(exp), -log10(obs))) +
        geom_line(aes(-log10(exp), -log10(upper)), color="gray") +
        geom_line(aes(-log10(exp), -log10(lower)), color="gray") +
        geom_point() +
        geom_abline(intercept=0, slope=1, color="red") +
        xlab(expression(paste(-log[10], "(expected P)"))) +
        ylab(expression(paste(-log[10], "(observed P)"))) +
        theme_bw()
}    

qqPlot(assoc$Score.pval[assoc$MAC >= 5])

Notice that we observe much less inflation than before, when we did not adjust for ancestry and relatedness.

Solution 4.1 (Data Studio)

Perform a single-variant association test for status. Adjust for sex, age, study, ancestry, and kinship in the model. Dont forget to consider the family parameter. Make a QQ plot of the p-values for all variants with MAC >= 5.

The first step is to fit the null model. We include PCs 1-4 and 7 as covariates in our model to adjust for ancestry, and we include a random effect proportional to the kinship matrix to adjust for genetic relatedness. Recall that with a binary outcome, we set family = binomial because we have a random effect, this will fit an approximate logistic mixed model using the GMMAT method.

nullmod.status <- fitNullModel(annot, 
                               outcome="status", 
                               covars=c("sex", "age", "study", paste0("PC", c(1:4,7))), 
                               cov.mat=kinship, 
                               family = binomial,
                               verbose=FALSE)

Exercise 4.2 (Application)

Use the GENESIS Null Model app on the BioData Catalyst powered by Seven Bridges platform to fit the a null model for height, adjusting for sex, age, study, ancestry, and kinship in the model, using the example 1000 Genomes data. Below are the inputs and settings to use for this analysis; we use the PCs and kinship matrix we computed using the PC-AiR and PC-Relate apps in the previous tutorials exercises.

  • Inputs
    • Phenotype file: sample_phenotype_pcs.RData
    • Relatedness matrix file: 1KG_phase3_subset_pcrelate_Matrix.RData
  • App Settings
    • Covariates: sex, age, study, PC1, PC2, PC3, PC4, PC5, PC6 (each as a different element)
    • Family: gaussian
    • Group Variate: study
    • Outcome: height
    • Two stage model: FALSE

The analysis will take a few minutes to run. You can find your analysis in the Tasks menu of your Project to check on its progress and see the results once it has completed.

Look at the .html report which covariates have significant (\(p < 0.05\)) associations with height in the null model?

Solution 4.2 (Application)

The steps to perform this analysis are as follows:

  • Copy the app to your project if it is not already there:
    • Click: Public Gallery > Apps > Browse
    • Search for GENESIS Null Model
    • Click: Copy > Select your project > Copy
  • Run the analysis in your project:
    • Click: Apps > GENESIS Null Model > Run
    • Specify the Inputs:
      • Phenotype file: sample_phenotype_pcs.RData
      • Relatedness matrix file: 1KG_phase3_subset_pcrelate_Matrix.RData
    • Specify the App Settings:
      • Covariates: sex, age, study, PC1, PC2, PC3, PC4, PC5, PC6 (each as a different element)
      • Family: gaussian
      • Group Variate: study
      • Outcome: height
      • Two stage model: FALSE
    • Click: Run

You can find the expected output of this analysis by looking at the existing task 6. 1KG Null Model in the Tasks menu of your Project. The output files are available in the Project, so you do not need to wait for your analysis to finish to move to the next exercise.

From looking at the .html report, we see that sex, study, and PC2 have significant associations with height in our null model.
